{
  "texts": [
    "Here, {T j, H i } denotes the wrapped distance between target j and herder i in the periodic domain.",
    "As is common in shepherding applications [8], [24], f (x) is repulsive (i.e., f (x)sign(x) ≥ 0 ∀x ∈ S), odd, and vanishes as the distance increases according to a characteristic interaction length L > 0.",
    "Additionally, we assume that the strength of the repulsion can be modulated by a gain K(t) > 0.",
    "Note that this is especially relevant where the herders are robotic swarms, such as in oil-spill containment [5].",
    "Instead, the diffusion term models Brownian motion, with B j (t) being independent standard Wiener processes and D > 0 being the diffusion coefficient.As the number of targets increases, tracking each agent in the population becomes progressively more cumbersome."
  ]
}